cted\nDocumentation/power/power_supply_class.rst-95-  to the platform is authentic(1) or non-authentic(0).\nDocumentation/power/power_supply_class.rst-96-\nDocumentation/power/power_supply_class.rst-97-HEALTH\nDocumentation/power/power_supply_class.rst-98-  represents health of the battery. Values corresponds to\nDocumentation/power/power_supply_class.rst-99-  POWER_SUPPLY_HEALTH_*, defined in battery.h.\nDocumentation/power/power_supply_class.rst-100-\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-22-\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-23-* Support for multiple chargers (e.g., a device with USB, AC, and solar panels)\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-24-\tA system may have multiple chargers (or power sources) and some of\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-25-\tthey may be activated at the same time. Each charger may have its\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-26-\town power-supply-class and each power-supply-class can provide\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-27-\tdifferent information about the battery status. This framework\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-28-\taggregates charger-related information from multiple sources and\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-29-\tshows combined information as a single power-supply-class.\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-30-\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-31-* Support for in suspend-to-RAM polling (with suspend_again callback)\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst:32:\tWhile the battery is being charged and the system is in suspend-to-RAM,\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-33-\twe may need to monitor the battery health by looking at the ambient or\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-34-\tbattery temperature. We can accomplish this by waking up the system\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-35-\tperiodically. However, such a method wakes up devices unnecessarily for\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-36-\tmonitoring the battery health and tasks, and user processes that are\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-37-\tsupposed to be kept suspended. That, in turn, incurs unnecessary power\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-38-\tconsumption and slow down charging process. Or even, such peak power\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-39-\tconsumption can stop chargers in the middle of charging\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-40-\t(external power input < device power consumption), which not\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-41-\tonly affects the charging time, but the lifespan of the battery.\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-42-\n--\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-101-If there are no other devices or tasks that want to use suspend_again\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-102-feature, the platform_suspend_ops may directly refer to cm_suspend_again\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-103-for its suspend_again callback.\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-104-\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-105-The cm_suspend_again() returns true (meaning \"I want to suspend again\")\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-106-if the system was woken up by Charger Manager and the polling\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-107-(in-suspend monitoring) results in \"normal\".\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-108-\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-109-4. Charger-Manager Data (struct charger_desc)\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-110-=============================================\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst:111:For each battery charged independently from other batteries (if a series of\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst:112:batteries are charged by a single charger, they are counted as one independent\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-113-battery), an instance of Charger Manager is attached to it. The following\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-114-\nDocumentation/power/charger-manager.rst-115-struct charger_d